find the thirteenth adjacent digits inthe 1000 digit number that have the greatest product.
what is the value of this product?

answer:

ok this seems like a sliding window problme thing, let me quickly brainstorm
since we only care about the product

0. first format the number into a list of number.
1. scan d number -> save the current product in a var (maybe can use take/drop thing)
2. move to the next number (cdr) and compare the product
- if new product = greater than last product, update that product
- else keep sliding.
3. ends when the number/list contains less than d elements


|#

; given a list of number, computes all of its product
(define (compute-product xs)
  (foldr * 1 xs)
  )
(compute-product '(1 5))
(compute-product '(1 5 7 8))

; main function
(define (greatest-product d n)
  (let ((list-of-numbers (map (λ (char) (- (char->integer char) (char->integer #\0)) ) (string->list (number->string n))) ))
    (define (helper xs d highest-so-far)
      (cond [(null? xs) highest-so-far] ;for guard
            [(< (length xs) d) highest-so-far] ;less than 4 elements, stop - needs to update cdddr to match 13 digit here
            [(> (compute-product (take xs d)) highest-so-far) (helper (cdr xs) d (compute-product (take xs d))) ] ;new product > old product, update
            [else (helper (cdr xs) d highest-so-far)] ; keep sliding
            )
      )
    (helper list-of-numbers d 0)
    )
  )
(greatest-product 13 1234567895555787789798)
(greatest-product 13 )
